  "articleSummary": "Thearticle argues that “generative UI” is not a single technology but a multi‑layered architectural pattern for LLM‑driven interfaces. It separates the stack into four distinct layers—product shell, UI composition model, runtime/transport, and agent/tool backend—and shows how conflating them leads to confusion, using concrete examples (AG‑UI vs A2UI, json‑render, CopilotKit, OpenAI Apps SDK, MCP Apps). The piece surveys the main approaches (tool‑to‑component rendering, declarative component catalogs, iframe mini‑apps) and frames the design trade‑off as a spectrum between developer control and agent freedom. Written in an analytical, tutorial‑style tone, it repeatedly uses the metaphor of “layers” and a “control spectrum” to guide readers—primarily developers and product engineers—through the emerging generative‑UI landscape.",
